 only Krshna among th=\r\ne various avatars of Vishnu is worshiped in those parts of India where Tant=\r\nras were the predominant scriptures that were followed. Rama is considered =\r\nas a part of Krshna. So along with Krshna nama, Rama nama japa is also done=\r\n, though there is no exclusive mass worship of Rama in these parts. \n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; =\r\n&gt;India has so many\n&gt;  flavors, that it is almost mind boggling.\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt;=\r\n*=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0 *\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt;On many subtle points, your mail was very th=\r\nought provoking. And I am sure I will keep pondering over various hints for=\r\n quite some time. But one point I want to make about Vedanta. I agree total=\r\nly with you. \n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt;Vedanta is the philosophy, not only of Shankara Adwait=\r\nha, but also that of Ramanujacharya, Madhavacharya, Chaitanya, Vallavachary=\r\na as well as the TantrAs. They are all Vedantas.\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt;Quite simple put, t=\r\nhere are two fundamental states of pure consciousness. Static, and dynamic.=\r\n Purusha and Shakti. The static consciousness is same all around in everyth=\r\ning, from the highest Avatara to the lowest stone. But the dynamic aspect o=\r\nf consciousness is NOT same in everything.\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt;Ramakrishna used to say, =\r\nKali in present in everyone, but Her Shakti is not same in everyone! This c=\r\nrucial point lies in the heart of Tantric Vedanta philosophy. By the proces=\r\ns of sadhana,\n&gt;  this dynamic aspect of consciousness can be enhanced in an=\r\n individual. This is the eternal purification of individual Chit-Shakti. Th=\r\ne purer it is, the stronger it becomes. This also accommodates for the idea=\r\n of vigyana. \n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt;That is why however much sadhana a person may do, he/s=\r\nhe will never ever attain to the level of a Rama or a Krshna. Its practical=\r\nly impossible. The difference is in their levels of individualized chit-sha=\r\nkti. Or that of a Rishi. Their Chit-Shakit is so powerful, so pure, so free=\r\n, that it can identify with the Universe and do things which are impossible=\r\n to imagine. Which we cannot. Ever.\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt;Once again, wishing everyone=\r\n a fruitful and auspicious Akshaya Tritiya!\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt;-Regards\n&gt; &gt;=C2=A0Rajars=\r\nhi\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt;awaktam wyaktimApannam manyantE mAmabuddhayah |\n&gt;=\r\n &gt;param bhAwamajAnanto mamAwyayamanuttamam ||[7:24]\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt;________=\r\n________________________\n&gt; &gt; From: Narasimha P.V.R. Rao &lt;pvr108@...&gt;\n&gt; &gt;To:=\r\n Vedic Wisdom &lt;vedic-wisdom@yahoogroups.com&gt; \n&gt; &gt;Sent: Thursday, 9 May 2013=\r\n 8:13 AM\n&gt; &gt;Subject: [vedic-wisdom] Re: Comparing Dasavataras!\n&gt; &gt; \n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt;=\r\n\n&gt; &gt;=C2=A0 \n&gt; &gt;Dear Rajarshi and others,\n&gt; &gt;=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;Have a great solar ec=\r\nlipse! This is a really nice occasion for extra \n&gt; meditation or extra homa=\r\nm or extra contemplation or extra \n&gt; philosophization.\n&gt; &gt;=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;*=C2=A0=\r\n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=\r\n=C2=A0 *\n&gt; &gt;=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;&gt; Now lets get into more subtle, precise analysis :)\n=\r\n&gt; &gt;=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;I asked for trouble, didn&#39;t I? :-)\n&gt; &gt;=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;*=C2=A0=C2=A0=\r\n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 =\r\n*\n&gt; &gt;=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;&gt; this apparent conflict between what Rishi Parashara\n&gt; &gt;&gt; s=\r\ntates and what this Purana states\n&gt; &gt;=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;There may be some confusion =\r\nregarding &quot;poornavatara&quot;.\n&gt; &gt;=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;As Parasara used it, the term &quot;poorn=\r\navatara&quot; does NOT mean &quot;the most complete or perfect avatara&quot;. It means a c=\r\nompletely divine avatara with no jivamsa. There can be more than one poorna=\r\nvataras. They are not necessarily &quot;equal&quot;.\n&gt; &gt;=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;To give a simplisit=\r\nc analogy, some jewllery may be gold mixed with some amount of\n&gt;  copper. I=\r\nf one jewllery is 100% pure gold, it\n&gt;  does not mean\n&gt;  it contains all th=\r\ne gold in the\n&gt;  world. It only means it has nothing other than gold. Simil=\r\narly, the four poornavataras mentioned by Parasara are 100% divine and do n=\r\not contain jivamsa. It does not mean they contain &quot;all the divinity&quot; in cos=\r\nmos.\n&gt; &gt;=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=\r\n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *\n&gt; &gt;=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;In fact, the very notion that=\r\n any one form can be &quot;the most complete or perfect avatara&quot; or &quot;one that pe=\r\nrsonifies entire divinity of Supreme Being&quot; or &quot;one equal to Supreme Being&quot;=\r\n is unacceptable and inconsistent with SB 1.3.30-31, which says that ANY fo=\r\nrm of Supreme Being is like a cloud in the sky, while Supreme Being is like=\r\n the sky containing all possible clouds.\n&gt; &gt;=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;Supreme Being is endo=\r\nwed with infinite qualities. Any form contains a finite number of those qua=\r\nlities. So no form can be &quot;equal to&quot; Supreme Being. SB 1.3.30-31 is clear i=\r\nn that regard.\n&gt; &gt;=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;If one\n&gt;  form is &quot;equal to&quot; supreme being and =\r\nothers are\n&gt;  not, you can conclude that that form is &quot;the best&quot;. If neithe=\r\nr form is &quot;equal to&quot; supreme being, how can you really compare the differen=\r\nt qualities of two forms?\n&gt; &gt;=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=\r\n=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *\n&gt; &gt;=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;Anyway=\r\n, this renders your (3) a meaningless issue. Whether that line refers to Kr=\r\nishna alone or not is irrelevant, for, in either case, &quot;swayam bhagavan&quot; ca=\r\nnnot mean &quot;a personification of the entirety of supreme being&quot;. Before you =\r\nwonder whether it refers to Krishna alone or not, first figure out what &quot;sw=\r\nayam bhagavan&quot; actually means, in a way that is not inconsistent with verse=\r\ns that follow! If no form is &quot;equal to&quot; supreme being and every form is a &quot;=\r\nsubset&quot; of supreme being (like a cloud in sky), what is the meaning of &quot;swa=\r\nyam bhagavan&quot;???\n&gt; &gt;=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0\n&gt;=\r\n  *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *\n&gt; &gt;=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;Regarding (4),=\r\n Parasara\n&gt;  identified 4 avataras as 100% divine, with no jivamsa, and ide=\r\nntified the source of divinity in each of them. He only gave objective info=\r\nrmation and did not give any subjective judgment on who is the best, which =\r\nSuta apparently did.\n&gt; &gt;=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;I have not read BV Purana. If you can quo=\r\nte some verses before and after, I can comment. Any comparison between avat=\r\naras WILL have to be under some subjective context. I don&#39;t know the contex=\r\nt of Suta&#39;s statement you allude to.\n&gt; &gt;=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;Though any comparison is =\r\nsubjective, I will be surprised if someone considers the other two poornava=\r\ntaras of Vishnu as the &quot;best&quot; avataras. But, I will not be surprised if dif=\r\nferent people consider Rama and Krishna as the most perfect avataras. Sun a=\r\nnd Moon are the luminaries and show soul and mind, which clearly have a pri=\r\nmary significance compared to other aspects of consciousness! So Rama and K=\r\nrishna are bound to be seen as the best by different people.\n&gt;  However, wh=\r\nat Suta\n&gt;  apparently said can only be a subjective view under some context=\r\n.\n&gt; &gt;=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=\r\n=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *\n&gt; &gt;=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;Regarding (2): Kala means a part=\r\n or a phase. Moon has 16 phases (representing 16 tithis, including Amavasya=\r\n and Pournima), but Sun has only one phase - he is always full and bright!\n=\r\n&gt; &gt;=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;Just like Moon, mind has many moods, even a perfected one. A p=\r\nerfected mind goes through those moods with full awareness of underlying re=\r\nality, whereas an imperfect mind experiences them under delusion. But it is=\r\n the nature of Moon/mind to have variations. Sun/soul OTOH has no such vari=\r\nations.\n&gt; &gt;=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;Krishna may show Vishwaroopa oneday, run away from bat=\r\ntlefield another day (e.g. Jarasandha), do amazing miracles oneday and play=\r\n clever tricks another day. There is a lot more variety to his personality =\r\nthan Rama&#39;s. Now, does that make him better or worse than Rama? Well, that\n=\r\n&gt;  is\n&gt;  a *subjective* matter.\n&gt; &gt;=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=\r\n=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *\n&gt; &gt;=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;=\r\nRegarding (1): Parasara said that paramatmamsa is present in several beings=\r\n such a planets, Brahma, Shiva, their consorts, etc. Grahas sustain the wor=\r\nld appearance in consciousness by grasping it based on karmaphala. So they =\r\nstand for different qualities of Vishnu that sustain the world appearance. =\r\nSo Vishnu&#39;s avataras are associated with grahas. But Pararsara said that av=\r\nataras can descend from the paramatmamsa present in several other beings (e=\r\n.g. Shiva, Parvati, Ashwins, Maruts etc). Unfortunately, we have meagre und=\r\nerstanding what various deities stand for, what forces play a role in creat=\r\ning, sustaining and destroying the world appearance in consciousness. Peopl=\r\ne talk too much about Vedanta (end of Veda) and there is hardly any underst=\r\nanding of Veda. When it comes to Puranic stories, we think in terms of\n&gt;  s=\r\nuperficial stories and not in terms of how it maps to what happens in consc=\