eration or emotions or pass=\r\nions can overturn the Rajadharma. His life is a lesson of what a true leade=\r\nr must be! Krshna, OTOH, had this immaculate detachment right from birth. I=\r\n am not taking his=C2=A0 supernatural feats into account. It is his singula=\r\nr and constant detachment from situations, from people, from environment, f=\r\nrom circumstances that mark his life. At the age of eight, he decides to le=\r\nave Vrindavana for Mathura. All his friends, his foster parents,\n&gt;  his vil=\r\nlage-folks who so loved him, pleaded with him that it would make no sense f=\r\nor him to leave the shelter, love and comfort of his happy, settled village=\r\n life and head into an unknown destiny and destination. Krshna tried to rea=\r\nson with them, then he understood that they won&#39;t understand, he promised h=\r\ne will return back once his work in Mathura is over. He never returned. Lat=\r\ner, much later, when the Gopis came to him asking him to participate in the=\r\nir dance, he obliged. But the moment some of them started getting jealous a=\r\nnd possessive of Krshna, he removed himself quietly from the scene, saying =\r\nthat he belongs to everyone equally and no one has any special right over h=\r\nim. When Shishupala abused Krshna, the later merely kept dropping flowers o=\r\nn the floor, smiling and counting. The moment the 100th abuse was over, he =\r\nswiftly cut off Shishupala&#39;s head and was back into his poise. But when Bhu=\r\nrishrava unfairly accused Krshna of being a revolutionist\n&gt;  and charlatan,=\r\n Krshna did not kill him. When Duryodhana, who used to think of Krshna as a=\r\nnother black magician, wanted to arrest him, Krshna showed his vikarala roo=\r\npa in the assembly of kings, yet he did not finish the enemies off. The ver=\r\ny next moment he was back into his own poised self. Never in the whole Maha=\r\nbharata is there one instance of his going overboard, never a single shade =\r\nof depression, equivocation, or lack of confidence in his actions, irrespec=\r\ntive of what others say or think of him. And then right in the middle of th=\r\ne greatest war he had the perfect equipoise to deliver the most sublime spi=\r\nritual philosophy. That is why his life remains the best ideal of Karma-Yog=\r\na. For a true Karma-Yogi by definition can never be dejected. It is impossi=\r\nble. Neither the action nor the results belong to the instrument. When runn=\r\ning away from the battle-field and killing Kaliya Yavana, or when advising =\r\nBheema to tear apart Jarashanda, or gesturing Bheema\n&gt;  to hit Duryodhana b=\r\nelow the waist, or getting Shikhandi to face Bhisma, Krshna, as if by some =\r\nDivine Intuition, knew exactly how the situations must be lined up which wo=\r\nuld cause the destruction of these people. This kind of knowledge cannot co=\r\nme by the rational thinking. But happens when one is constantly and conscio=\r\nusly connected to the Universal Force. We do not find these kind of complex=\r\n situations in the Rama Avatara, at least in the Valmiki Ramayana. Of cours=\r\ne, if we take the Adhbut Ramayana or such other auxilliary texts and retell=\r\ning, we get a different picture. In the Adbhuta Ramayana we have a 1000 hea=\r\nded demon attacking Rama after he kills Ravana, and then Sita turns into Ad=\r\nya Shakti and demolishes the 1000 headed demon and Rama worships her. But i=\r\nf we take only the Ramayana and the Mahabharata, the picture that emerges i=\r\ns very clear. Rama is the embodiment of Sattwic mind. Therefore he displays=\r\n all the great characteristics of satwa, chief\n&gt;  of which is self-control,=\r\n as well as the occasional sadness caused due to separation from his wife S=\r\nita whom, at least until Ravana was destroyed, he loved very dearly. Satwa =\r\nguna creates a true saint, but can also cause some grief when the stability=\r\n is shaken. Krshna was gunatita. He had no attachment to anything in this w=\r\norld - man, women, deva,